observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
a. Municipal General Services Officer and Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain the Property Cards (PCs) and PPE Ledger Cards (PPELCs), respectively, for each class of PPE;
b. Inventory Committee to strictly follow the preliminary activities to obtain complete preliminary records prior to inventory taking and revise the Physical Inventory Plan based on the updated records and RPCPPE;
c. Inventory Committee to tag all PPE items counted with property stickers with complete vital information and ensure that tags/stickers are attached to prominent and secure portions of the property to facilitate the easy identification of government property;
d. Municipal General Services Officer to prepare and maintain Property Acknowledgement Receipts (PARs) upon issuance of PPE and ensure its renewal every three years or every time there is a change in accountability or custodianships; and
e. Municipal General Services Officer, Municipal Accountant and the Inventory Committee to ensure full and timely derecognition of missing/non-existent PPEs as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
a. Municipal Assessor to assist the Municipal Engineer in the assessment of the fair value of the road lot components of the Road Networks;
b. Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal General Services Officer the complete description and cost segregation of road components;
c. Municipal General Services Officer to maintain the prescribed Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components; and
d. Municipal Accountant to: • maintain Local Road Network Ledger Cards for all roads and its components and recompute the depreciation per road components, except for the road lot in accordance with the guidelines set in COA Circular No. 2015-008 and make the necessary adjustments in the books of account; and • disclose the complete information of the Road Network System in accordance with the prescribed format under COA Circular No. 2015-008.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. require the Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of all of the local roads and submit the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network (RPCLRN);
b. instruct the Municipal Treasurer to maintain the Local Road Network Property Card (LRNPC) and Local Road Network Card (LRNLC);
c. request the Municipal Engineer to provide the description and cost segregation of road components constructed from CY 2016 up to present; and
d. direct the Municipal Accountant to keep and maintain Local Road Network Ledger Card and reconcile the same with the result of the physical inventory, recognize depreciation expense and make necessary adjustments.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the concerned:
a. Municipal General Services Officer and the Municipal Accountant to maintain property cards and PPE Ledger Cards, respectively, and updating the Property Cards and PPE Ledger Cards, respectively, and facilitate the reconciliation of both records;
b. Municipal General Services Officer and the Municipal Accountant to complete the physical count of the Municipality’s PPE and to accomplish the RPCPPE completely and properly;
c. Municipal Accountant to determine the cause/s of the discrepancy and prepare the necessary adjustments in the books;
d. Municipal General Services Officer to facilitate the monitoring and control of property thru the updating and/or renewal of PAR for pinpointing of the accountability in case of transfer of accountable officer and loss of/or damage to government property; and
e. Inventory Committee to fast-track the completion of the physical count of the PPE, and accomplish the RPCPPE completely and properly.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
require the immediate liquidation by concerned Municipal employees of the outstanding cash advances totaling P143,130.00 in compliance with COA Circular Nos. 97-002.  Henceforth, see to it that all outstanding cash advances are fully liquidated at the end of the year;
refrain from granting cash advances to officers and employees with outstanding cash advances;
avail of the legal and administrative remedies provided under Sections 9.1 and 9.3 of COA Circular No. 2012-004 to enforce liquidation of long outstanding cash advances.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal General Services Officer to reconcile the RPCPPE with the books of accounts to avoid the incurrence of differences in their records. 

Further, to facilitate the reconciliation, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant and Municipal General Services Officers:

a. observe proper maintenance and updating of the PPELCs and PCs;



b. provide the complete and necessary information in both records, and;



c. effect the necessary adjustments in their records.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

a. require the Accountable Officers to liquidate their cash advances as soon as the purpose for which it was granted has been served and strictly adhere to the requirements of COA Circular No. 97-002;




b. enforce the policy of deducting from the salary of concerned Accountable Officers any cash advance not settled after the lapse of the prescribed period;

c. strictly implement the regulation that no additional cash advances shall be granted unless the previous cash given is first settled; and,

d. issue demand letter for cash advances not settled within the prescribed period.

In addition, we recommended that the cash advances be supported with documentary evidence to support the amount of cash advance to avoid the granting of excessive cash advances.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the MSWD Officer, Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to:

a. Refrain from paying disbursements thru cash advance, instead issue check directly payable in the name of the creditor/payee to whom payment is due;

b. strictly comply with the revenue regulation on withholding of taxes for the procurement of goods and services;



c. submit liquidation report/ Disbursement Voucher to the Auditor with complete documentary requirements to prevent the issuance of Notice of Suspension/ Disallowance in audit; and



d. follow the procurement laws in the purchases of goods and services.
